t (lateral) alveolar consonant. However, the way the husband pronounces it [ol], with a mid-back-rounded-tense vowel [o] replacing the [ɔɪ] (1). The vowel [ɔ] is more often applied to Northern American English dialects rather than Southern (2). Additionally, the only difference between [ɔ] and [o] is the tenseness, and the tenseness of [o] that is present in the Southern American English pronunciation of “oil” means that position of the tongue and lips is more extreme and requires greater muscle usage. Because of this, the [ɪ] appears deleted from this pronunciation as well. The wife in the video does not appear to have a Southern American English accent herself, so to her she is criticizing the deletion of the lax vowel that bridges the initial vowel and ending consonant together in the Standardized American English pronunciation of “oil”.%0a%3c %0a%3c This criticized pronunciation variant of “oil” belongs to the Southern American English dialect, as established in the video and by the video’s title. The Southern American English dialect pronounces it similar to the word “ol”, a shortened version of “old”.%0a%3c %0a%3c (1) https://www.ling.upenn.edu/courses/Fall_2014/ling115/phonetics.html%0a%3c %0a%3c (2) https://repository.library.georgetown.edu/bitstream/handle/10822/553139/allbrittenrachael.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%